at ran this session. These are the raw materials for your retrospective — do not ignore them.\n\nCRITICAL: Run `codeharness stats --save` to generate the cost report. Read `_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/cost-report.md` and include cost analysis in the retrospective.\n\nCRITICAL: The session issues log contains `## Token Report` sections from each subagent. Aggregate these to understand WHERE tokens were spent inside subagents (not just the parent). Look for:\n- Which subagent phases had the most tool calls?\n- Which subagents read the same files repeatedly?\n- Which Bash commands produced the largest outputs?\n- What redundant operations were reported?\nInclude this subagent-level breakdown in the cost analysis section.\n\nCONTEXT: This session was a no-op — all 74 stories across 17 epics (0-16) were already done. The only action taken was reconciling stale working-tree state (sprint-state.json had stories 16-7 and 16-8 reverted to `review` despite being committed as `done`). The session issues log contains data from the PREVIOUS session's subagents (session 52), not this one.\n\nProduce a retrospective that covers:\n1. **Session summary** — which stories were attempted, their outcomes, time spent\n2. **Issues analysis** — categorize and analyze all issues from the session log:\n   - Bugs discovered during implementation or verification\n   - Workarounds applied (tech debt introduced this session)\n   - Code quality concerns raised by reviewers\n   - Verification gaps (escalated ACs, weak evidence)\n   - Tooling/infrastructure problems (sandbox, permissions, CLI issues)\n3. **Cost analysis** — from the cost report:\n   - Total API-equivalent cost this sprint\n   - Cost per phase (which phases are most expensive?)\n   - Cost per story (which stories cost the most and why?)\n   - Wasted spend (no-op sessions, failed verifications, retries)\n   - Cost optimization opportunities:\n     * Stories that should use unit-testable verification instead of Docker\n     * Phases that could be cheaper (e.g., lighter retros for no-op sessions)\n     * Subagent prompts that could be trimmed to reduce cache writes\n     * Average cost per story vs target (flag if trending up)\n4. **What went well** — stories completed, bugs fixed, process improvements\n5. **What went wrong** — failures, blockers, stuck stories, wasted iterations\n6. **Lessons learned** — patterns to repeat or avoid\n7. **Action items** — concrete next steps, split into:\n   - Fix now (before next session)\n   - Fix soon (next sprint)\n   - Backlog (track but not urgent)\n   - Cost optimization (specific actions to reduce token consumption)\n\nWrite the retrospective to _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/session-retro-2026-03-28.md. If a session retro for today already exists, append to it with a `---` separator and timestamp.\n\nDo NOT ask the user any questions — proceed autonomously.\nDo NOT run git commit. Do NOT run git add. Do NOT modify sprint-status.yaml.","agentId":"a2c8618c8e15cb363","agentType":"general-purpose","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Retrospective written to `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/session-retro-2026-03-28.md` (appended after separator).\n\nKey findings:\n\n- **Session 53 was a no-op.** All 74 stories already done. Only action: reconciling sprint-state.json where 16-7/16-8 had reverted to `review`.\n- **Total sprint cost: $896.45** across 6,537 API calls. Average $4.17/story.\n- **Verification is 53.2% of cost** ($476.61). Dev-story is only 3.4% ($30.07) — the cheapest phase.\n- **26.5% of spend ($237.39) is unattributed** to any story — orchestrator overhead, no-op sessions, retros.\n- **Subagent redundancy:** npm test run 2-4 times per subagent phase. Worst case: 4 runs in 16-7 verification. vitest run separately for test vs coverage when one run would suffice.\n- **TodoWrite called 111 times ($15.24)** despite being banned.\n- **Top cost optimization:** Short-circuit no-op sessions, capt